==English==
===Noun===
[[Category:English nouns]]
'''git'''
#(''British slang'') A [[stupid]] or [[unpleasant]] person. The origins of the word are old (used for at least the last 70 years and probably considerably more) and in tune with many slang or abusive words, often has a sexual overtone or involves the slandering of one or both parents. "Git" was a term used to refer to the [[illegitimate]] son of a [[prostitute]], putting an altogether more insulting spin on it than is generally taken today.  In modern British parlance, the true meaning of "git" (and it's associated implication about one's mother) has become greatly diluted and being called a git would not generally cause great offence. Friends may even use the term in, almost affectionate, fun-poking at each other whilst older generations or strangers may not be as forgiving or relaxed on being so-called. As with a lot of slang, the intention behind the word may be subtly altered when used in conjunction with another. To illustrate; the phrase "you dopey git" has an almost jokey feel, whereas "you stupid git" has a fairly unmistakable insulting air to it. Git, however, does not carry the impact of other slang words and "you stupid git" in no way has the impact of "you stupid [[wanker]]". On a scale of 1-5, that word rates about 4 whereas "git" can vary (according to application) from a 2 to 4.

